---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SiteHeader from '../../components/SiteHeader.astro';
import SiteFooter from '../../components/SiteFooter.astro';

const facts = [
  { term: 'Role', detail: 'Senior Engineering Manager, BNPL platform' },
  {
    term: 'Span',
    detail: 'From a seven-person team to a first-class partner on the core checkout platform',
  },
  { term: 'Scale', detail: "~$40B in annual platform volume across international markets" },
  {
    term: 'Headline outcomes',
    detail:
      'Maintainer standing in the shared checkout codebase in two quarters · review cycle from two weeks to ship-when-done · 4× experiment throughput driving $180M incremental TPV',
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="Leading BNPL platform engineering at PayPal: Munad Mahinoor"
  description="A case study in earning a team the right to operate as a first-class engineering partner inside one of PayPal's most critical codebases."
>
  <SiteHeader slot="header" currentPath="/work" />

  <section class="page-intro">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="kicker">Case study 01</p>
      <h1>Leading BNPL platform engineering at PayPal</h1>
      <p class="standfirst">
        When I joined PayPal's Buy-Now-Pay-Later team in 2022, we were seven engineers with an
        ambitious roadmap and no reliable path to ship it. Every change we owned ran through PayPal's
        core checkout platform, and we had no standing there. This is how I turned a dependent
        team into a first-class engineering partner in one of the company's most critical
        codebases, and the framework we left behind so other teams could do the same.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <hr class="divider-stripe divider-stripe--muted container-hr" />

  <section class="case-body">
    <div class="container">
      <dl class="facts" aria-label="At a glance">
        {
          facts.map((f) => (
            <div class="facts__row">
              <dt>{f.term}</dt>
              <dd>{f.detail}</dd>
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </dl>

      <p>
        I joined PayPal's Buy-Now-Pay-Later team in 2022 to lead seven engineers with an
        ambitious credit product roadmap and no reliable path to ship it. Every change we owned ran
        through the company's core checkout codebase, a domain where we had no independent
        standing. As with any critical shared codebase, changes from outside teams moved through
        conservative, high touch review, and our pull requests sat behind weeks of manual
        walkthroughs. Priority depended on relationships rather than an agreed process, and our
        delivery speed depended on the goodwill we could borrow rather than on any process we
        controlled.
      </p>
      <p>
        The real problem was not the review queue. No one had defined what my team actually was:
        what we owned, what we were accountable for, and on what terms we were allowed to touch a
        codebase the company depended on to keep running. Until that was settled, every delivery
        conversation kept collapsing back into a negotiation. My goal was to stop operating as a
        supervised guest in someone else's codebase and become a first-class engineering partner
        with standing of our own.
      </p>
      <p>
        I began with the organizational problem rather than the technical one. I went to the platform's leadership with a
        deliberately lopsided proposal: we would make no claim on ownership of their codebase,
        their architecture, or their roadmap, and in return they would treat my engineers like
        new hires on their own team, with the same onboarding, the same access, and the same
        ramp up anyone joining their team would get. I paired that with a single point of
        accountability: if something we shipped broke, my team took accountability for it, not a
        platform engineer who happened to approve the pull request. Over the next two quarters I
        earned that access in the open. I integrated my team into both our own roadmap and the
        platform's, put junior engineers to work as genuine capacity against the platform team's
        own goals, and built relationships at the staff engineer level so the technical trust ran
        peer to peer. Then I proposed a one quarter probationary period and invited extreme
        scrutiny of everything we shipped, because a team that welcomes hard review is a team you
        stop needing to police. Once the model held, I wrote it up as a repeatable ladder of
        trust: the concrete stages a partner team moves through, from supervised contributions to
        full maintainer standing, so the next team would not have to reinvent the path we had
        walked.
      </p>
      <p>
        Within two quarters my team held maintainer standing and owned production issues end to
        end. The review cycle went from a two-week walkthrough to ship-when-done, which roughly
        doubled our project output inside the shared codebase. After full integration, the team
        delivered four times as many experiments per quarter, generating nearly $180M in
        additional total payment volume. The onboarding program we built grew the platform's
        contributor roster to twenty engineers across multiple teams through a quarterly intake,
        and the following year my team was named a critical partner on a ground-up overhaul of
        the checkout experience.
      </p>

      <hr class="divider-stripe divider-stripe--muted cta-hr" />

      <p class="cta">
        There is more to this story than fits on a page: the failures along the way, what I
        would do differently, and how the framework traveled. If it resonates, I would genuinely
        enjoy comparing notes. Find me on
        {' '}
        <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/munadmahinoor" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
          LinkedIn
        </a>
        {' '}or{' '}
        <a href="mailto:mahinoormunad@gmail.com">email me directly</a>.
      </p>

      <p class="back-link">
        <a href="/work">Back to selected work</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <SiteFooter slot="footer" />
</Base>

<style>
  .page-intro {
    padding-block: var(--space-5) var(--space-3);
  }
  .standfirst {
    font-size: var(--fs-subhead);
    line-height: var(--leading-heading);
    color: var(--color-muted);
    max-width: var(--measure);
    margin-top: var(--space-2);
  }

  .container-hr {
    max-width: var(--container);
    margin-inline: auto;
    margin-block: var(--space-3);
  }

  .case-body {
    padding-block: var(--space-2) var(--space-7);
  }
  .case-body p {
    max-width: var(--measure);
  }

  /* At a glance facts block: semantic definition list, not a layout table. */
  .facts {
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-5);
    padding: 0;
    max-width: var(--measure);
    border-top: var(--border-hair) solid var(--color-rule-faint);
  }
  .facts__row {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: minmax(8rem, 12rem) 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-2) var(--space-3);
    padding-block: var(--space-2);
    border-bottom: var(--border-hair) solid var(--color-rule-faint);
  }
  .facts dt {
    font-size: var(--fs-14);
    font-weight: var(--fw-bold);
    letter-spacing: var(--tracking-wide);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-muted);
    margin: 0;
  }
  .facts dd {
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--color-ink);
  }
  @media (max-width: 34rem) {
    .facts__row {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: var(--space-1);
    }
  }

  .cta-hr {
    margin-block: var(--space-6) var(--space-4);
  }
  .cta {
    max-width: var(--measure);
    font-size: var(--fs-18);
  }

  .back-link {
    margin-top: var(--space-6);
    font-size: var(--fs-16);
    font-weight: var(--fw-medium);
  }
</style>
